\(BALS\) is the basal area share [0-1] of spruce dominant trees, the 100 largest trees per ha e.g. the 6 largest trees (in dbh) in a 25x25m cell.

The trees should be ordered from larger to smaller diameter and select the \(N{trees}\). The number of trees selected should be:

\[ N_{trees}=\frac{cellArea*100}{10000} \]

Then \(BALS\) in the cell will be:

\[ BALS=\frac{\sum_{N_{trees}}^{1} BA}{TotalBA} \]

\(TotalBA\) refers to the total BA of all the trees in the cell, also including those that are not beetle host trees.

\(baSpr\) is the basal area share [0-1] of spruce trees across all biomass available in the cell including not host trees.

Windthrow-induced susceptibility

Id Formulation Param. Definition Ref.
\[S_{w_{default}}\] \[S_w=\begin{cases}1 & \text{if}\ W_{bhb} / maxW_{bhb} > 1\\W_{bhb} / maxW_{bhb} & \text{else}\ \end{cases}\] Wind throw susceptibility index scaled between 0 and 1 per cell and year (S_w) [1]
\[S_{w1}\] \[ S_w=\frac{killedwindhostBiomass_{cell}}{totalBiomass_{cell}} \]

\(W_{bhb}\) (windthrowBeetleHostBiomass): Windthrown beetle host biomass in focal cell and year [t/ha (Simulation.Wind.BeetleHostBiomassDown)

NOTICED!: changed that after a year disappears! this affects how long a windthrown log is available as host with is ~2 years (17 months) according to [4]

\(maxW_{bhb}\) (maxWindthrowBeetleHost):Maximum potential beetle host biomass on cell [t/ha] (\(maxW\_{bhb} = CellmaxBiomass * CellArea * 0.0001 * SiWMaxCoeff[0-1]\)

\(SiWMaxCoeff\) is a user defined parameter to scale the max biomass proportion that could be considered as the max windthrow beetle host biomass [0-1]

\(CellmaxBiomass\) is the max biomass per cell defined by the user in the LandType parameter file, if it is not defined it will take the value 0 and therefore the \(S_w\) would be also 1.

Time component of wind susceptibility

\(S_w\) values should be available for two years (current year and the year before), e.g. if the wind damage happened in year t=1, the max value for \(S_w\) would be max(\(S_{w0}\), \(S_{w1}\)), but even if the max value for t=1 is \(S_{w0}\), for t=2 the maximum value would be between max(\(S_{w1}\), \(S_{w2}\)), because the the wind-thrown logs are available as host ~2 years (17 months) according to [4].

Dispersal

Beetle generations
Attribute Id Formulation Parameters Definition Ref.
Generations of beetle in one year \(Gen1\) \[Gen=\begin{cases}0 & \text{if}\ G=0\\1 & \text{if}\ 0<G<=0.2\\2 & \text{if}\ 0.2<G<=0.6\\3 & \text{if}\ 0.6<G\end{cases}\]

r = 3.307963

m = 1.980938

 Relationship between relative degree day sum and beetle hazard (see Figure 6 and 7 in Baier et al. 2007) Baier et al. 2007 and Netherer and Nopp-Mayr 2005.

If generations take value 2 or 3 then we have dispersal on the same year of 1 or 2 kernels distance respectively.

If the generation value is higher than 1 then we applied the kernel dispersal over the cells that had an infestation.

Attribute Id Formulation Param. Definition Ref.
Beetle dispersal if Generations is >1 \(K\) \[K=e^-({\frac{\frac{D}{4.5}}{40.5*4}})^2\] iLand formulation Fahse and Heurich 2011

The \(K\) value used will be the highest value of the cell, in case this cell is exposed to higher pressure (K values) from nearby cells that were already infected.

The kernel is scaled (values sum more than one) and the value is used to substitude the Pressure of the cells with a kernel value:

\[ R_{cell}=S_{cell}*K \]

When the new \(R_{cell}\) value is calculated for the cells that were not previously infected and exposed to a K value, then we will run again:

\[B_{inf}=Binomial(R_{cell})\]

only for those cells that were not previously infected.

If \(G=3\) then we will do this same process twice.

When all of this is done we will have a final map identifying which cells are infected by beetle and which ones are not, and we can move to the “kill” trees using the mortality formulation.

\(D\) will take a maximum value of 50m so the kernel wont be as large as the whole landscape.

Mortality

Attribute Id Formulation Param. Definition Ref.
Mortality \(M_{btl_{default}}\) * \[M_{btl}=\frac{S_{coh}+P_{btl}}{2}\]
Mortality \(M_{btl1}\) \[M_{btl}=S_{coh}*R_{cell}\]

*NOTICED! write the correct definition of mortality as in the code, it is not exaclty like this!

Then the number of trees killed in each cohort is defined as:

\[ Killed_{cohort}=Binomial(M_{btl}, N_{cohort}) \]

Attribute Id Formulation Param. Definition Ref.
\(default\) \[S_{coh}=\frac{S_{d}+S_{a_{coh}}}{2}\]
Cohort susceptibility to being killed \(S_{coh_{default}}\) \[S_{coh}=max(\frac{S_{d}+S_{a_{coh}}}{2}, S_{wn})\]
Cohort susceptibility to being killed \(S_{coh}1\) \[S_{coh}=max(\frac{S_{d}+S_{dbh_{coh}}}{2}, S_{wn})\]
Cohort susceptibility to being killed \(S_{coh}2\) \[S_{coh}=wS_{d_{coh}}*S_{d}+wS_{dbh_{coh}}*S_{dbh_{coh}} + wS_{wn}* S_{wn} + wS_{a_{coh}} * S_{a_{coh}}\]
